Freud pursued his clinical investigation of nervous disorders, blazing a path into the unplumbed recesses of human consciousness and desire. Yet this revolutionary who was overthrowing cherished notions of human rationality and sexuality was, in his politics and personal habits, in many ways conservative, Roudinesco shows. In his chauvinistic attitudes toward women, and in his stubborn refusal to acknowledge the growing threat of Hitler until it was nearly too late, even the analytically-minded Freud had his blind spots. Alert to his intellectual complexity—the numerous tensions in his character and thought that remained unresolved—Roudinesco ultimately views Freud less as a scientific thinker than as the master interpreter of civilization and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPsychoanalysisxHistory. 0aPsychoanalystszAustriavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Social Scientists & Psychologists.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063858540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067497452440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674974524423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674974524.jpg  a978-3-11-063858-5  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles